                                                                                                                       7                                      BCCI asks for sporting pitches
            A STAFF REPORTER                      
	Calcutta: The Board of Control for Cricket in India (BCCI) seems to have learnt from the Kotla pitch fiasco, when the fifth one-day International between India and Sri Lanka (December 27, last year) was called off due to a dangerous.         
	The BCCI brass does not want to take any chance on the pitch and ground conditions for the upcoming South Africa. Therefore, the Board has already sent an email to all the five staging centres, Nagpur and Kolkata (for the Test matches) and Jaipur, Kanpur, Ahmedabad (for ODIs), instructing them to prepare sporting pitches.         
	The email from BCCI secretary N. Srinivasan, addressed to the secretaries of the five staging associations, states that the secretaries should instruct their respective curators to prepare sporting wicket.         
	Prabir Mukherjee, curator of the CAB, admitted that he has received a copy of that letter.         
	Yes, I have received the instructions from the BCCI secretary. This is the first time that BCCI has officially communicated on what should be the nature of the pitch, the veteran curator said.         
	He also informed reporters that till the Test match (starting from February 14), no other competitive matches (CAB club matches) will be held at the Eden.  
